# 2. analogWrite()

## Definition

Unlike `analogRead()`, `analogWrite()` does not generate a true analog voltage.

Instead, it generates a **Pulse Width Modulated (PWM)** signal that simulates analog output.

The output values range from:

```text id="0u7b14"
0 to 255
```

because Arduino UNO uses an **8-bit PWM resolution**.

---

## Syntax

```cpp id="6jlwmj"
analogWrite(pin, value);
```

Example:

```cpp id="h2jlwm"
analogWrite(9, 128);
```

---

## PWM Values

| Value | Duty Cycle | Effective Output  |
| ----- | ---------- | ----------------- |
| 0     | 0%         | OFF               |
| 64    | 25%        | Low brightness    |
| 128   | 50%        | Medium brightness |
| 192   | 75%        | High brightness   |
| 255   | 100%       | Fully ON          |

---

## Example

```cpp id="4jlwmj"
analogWrite(9, 200);
```

This generates a PWM signal with approximately 78% duty cycle.

---

## Applications of analogWrite()

* LED brightness control
* Motor speed control
* Fan speed regulation
* Heater power control
* Audio tone generation

---

## IoT Example

### Smart Street Lighting

A smart street light uses an LDR to measure ambient light.

During the evening, the controller uses:

```cpp id="6jljwj"
analogWrite(ledPin, brightness);
```

to gradually increase street light brightness.

This saves energy and extends lamp lifetime.

