# What is PWM?

PWM stands for **Pulse Width Modulation**.

PWM is a technique used to simulate analog voltage using a digital signal.

Instead of changing voltage continuously, the microcontroller rapidly switches the output ON and OFF.

By changing the percentage of time the signal stays ON, different average voltages can be produced.

---

## Duty Cycle

The percentage of time the signal remains HIGH during one complete cycle is called the **duty cycle**.

Mathematically:

```text id="g1a0yo"
Duty Cycle = (ON Time / Total Time) × 100
```

---

## Example

### 25% Duty Cycle

```text id="n3t4yz"
HIGH ___
LOW  ___________
```

Average output voltage:

```text id="d52od2"
1.25V
```

---

### 50% Duty Cycle

```text id="vcgvya"
HIGH _____
LOW  _____
```

Average output voltage:

```text id="ih76mv"
2.5V
```

---

### 100% Duty Cycle

```text id="c1crf4"
HIGH ____________
```

Average output voltage:

```text id="lkx62n"
5V
```

---

# Why is PWM Used?

Generating true analog voltages requires Digital-to-Analog Converters (DACs), which increase system complexity and cost.

PWM provides a simple and efficient alternative using ordinary digital pins.

Advantages include:

* Low cost implementation
* High efficiency
* Low power loss
* Simple hardware requirements
* Fine control over output power

---

# Arduino PWM Pins

On Arduino UNO, PWM is available on:

```text id="w5tb75"
3, 5, 6, 9, 10 and 11
```

These pins are marked with the symbol:

```text id="ehzkt1"
~
```

---

# Comparison Between analogRead() and analogWrite()

| Parameter      | analogRead()        | analogWrite()       |
| -------------- | ------------------- | ------------------- |
| Purpose        | Read analog voltage | Generate PWM output |
| Pin Type       | Analog input pins   | PWM output pins     |
| Data Flow      | Input               | Output              |
| Resolution     | 10-bit              | 8-bit               |
| Range          | 0–1023              | 0–255               |
| Hardware Used  | ADC                 | PWM Timer           |
| Example Device | LDR Sensor          | LED or Motor        |

